{
  "type": "function",
  "function": {
    "name": "memory_query",
    "description": "Tool-only: call once; no assistant text outside tool_calls. Maze move — EXPLORE one corridor of the graph. Traverse the agent's unified knowledge/memory graph (LightRAG) — one graph of entities, relations, and document chunks. Knowledge and memory are the same store: indexed domain knowledge (ontology, documentation, rules, facts) AND previously recorded thread_memory / global_memory notes and past conversations all live as nodes/edges here. This is the targeted access mechanism — use it to look up a specific fact, recall something saved earlier, follow an association between known entities, or check reference material when the current context blocks (<knowledge_graph>, <thread_memory>, <global_memory>) do not already contain it. Those blocks are only one prior sample of the graph, not the whole graph. Returns a focused answer without rebuilding the full context.\n\nWhen to use: a missing fact; an association/relation between two known entities; reference material to recover from a tool or validation error; an apparent contradiction to confirm against the graph; a domain how-to; discovery — whether an implementation or policy already exists ('Where is X handled?', 'What does bridges_contract.md say about channel bridges?', 'Is there an existing memory_query route?').\n\nWhen NOT to use: something already present in <knowledge_graph>/<thread_memory>/<global_memory> — answer directly (do not repeat the lookup). A broad multi-entity cross-reference or full re-traverse — that is reflect (do not pack it into one mega-query). Live file contents or repo paths on disk — that needs cli_intent after graph lookup if still missing.\n\nThis is a tool you call directly — do NOT wrap it in cli_intent or run 'memory_query' as a shell command (it is an FSM route, not an OS binary); pass your question in the query field.\n\nQuery rules: name the concrete entities, policies, or document files you know (graph retrieval on a vague query returns poorly); ask relation questions directly ('How does X relate to Y?'); keep one focused question per call; for a follow-up, anchor on an entity named in the prior observation.",
    "parameters": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "query": {
          "type": "string",
          "minLength": 1,
          "maxLength": 4000,
          "description": "Specific question to traverse the unified knowledge/memory graph. Be precise and name entities — the query is passed directly to the graph retrieval engine. Examples: a fact ('What is the retention policy for archived threads?'); an association ('How does the egress_router relate to the channel field in X-Threlium-Route?'); error recovery ('How do I declare prefixes inside sh:sparql in shacl_sparql.md?'); existing implementation ('Where is email ingress handled in the FSM?', 'What is the shared bridge contract for matrix and email channels?')."
        },
        "reasoning": {
          "type": "string",
          "minLength": 1,
          "maxLength": 2000,
          "description": "Why this knowledge lookup is needed — short text for logs."
        }
      },
      "required": ["query", "reasoning"],
      "additionalProperties": false
    }
  }
}
